17 SUMMARY
1188 This amendment makes the following changes to the bill.
19 1. It clarifies the provisions regarding cannabis delivery transactions and specified
20 events to allow licensees to use the tracking system established by the Department of
21 Administrative and Financial Services, Office of Cannabis Policy to track delivery
22 transactions and sales at specified events in the same manner as transactions conducted
23 within a cannabis store.
24 2. It removes the provisions of the bill that eliminate cannabis purchase limits.
25 3. It clarifies that a natural person licensed under the Maine Revised Statutes, Title
26 28-B or a principal, contractor, employee or other support staff of the licensee must be on
27 the licensee's premises at all times.
28 4. It changes, rather than eliminates, requirements regarding the inspection of licensed
29 premises. The amendment retains the existing provisions in law regarding inspections by
30 the office and by an official authorized by the municipality, but it removes the ability for a
31 criminal justice agency to inspect any part of a licensed premises that is not open to the
32 public, except when the licensee has voluntarily allowed the law enforcement officer to
33 enter, entry is authorized by a warrant issued by a duly authorized justice, judge or justice
34 of the peace or entry is authorized in accordance with a recognized exception to the warrant
35 requirement.
36 5. It removes the provisions that would allow advertising, marketing, labeling or
37 packaging to contain qualifying patients' testimonial of how cannabis for medical use has
38 provided palliative or therapeutic effects for the patients' conditions.
39 6. It removes the provisions related to excise tax laws as they apply to cannabis
40 biomass.
